Three objections follow. The first turns upon the text of S. Gregory, Fides uon habet meritum cui humana ratio praebet experimentum: enquiry into matters of saith is therefore inexpedient and dan- gerous. Wyclifse replies by arguing in favour of free enquiry, so long as it is conducted in a be- coming spirit of reverence, and confined to the learned. He maintains that all articles of faith are susceptible of demonstration‚ though not all in the same manner.
